{{Infobox language |name=Oroqen |states=[[People's Republic of China|China]] |region=[[Inner Mongolia]] and [[Heilongjiang]] |speakers=1,200 |date=2009 |ref = <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/orh|title=Oroqen|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-05-07|language=en}}</ref> |familycolor=Altaic |fam1=[[Tungusic languages|Tungusic]] |fam2=Northern |fam3=Evenki |iso3=orh |glotto=oroq1238 |glottorefname=Oroqen }}
'''Oroqen''' (also known as Orochon, Oronchon, Olunchun, Elunchun, Ulunchun) is a [[Northern Tungusic languages|Northern Tungusic]] language spoken in the [[People's Republic of China]]. Dialects are Gankui and Heilongjiang. Gankui is the standard dialect.<ref>Raymond G. Gordon Jr., ed. 2005, ''Ethnologue: Languages of the World''. 15th edition. Dallas Summer Institute of Linguistics.</ref> It is spoken by the [[Oroqen people]] of [[Inner Mongolia]] (predominantly the [[Oroqin Autonomous Banner]]) and [[Heilongjiang]] in [[Northeastern China|Northeast]] [[People's Republic of China|China]].
Currently, the Oroqen language is still unwritten. However, the majority of the Oroqen are capable of reading and writing [[Chinese language|Chinese]] and some can also speak the [[Daur language|Daur]] language.
==Geographic distribution== Oroqen is spoken in the following counties of China (''Ethnologue'').
*[[Heilongjiang province]] **[[Da Hinggan Ling]]: [[Huma County]] and [[Tahe County]] **[[Heihe]]: [[Xunke County]] **[[Yichun, Heilongjiang|Yichun]]: [[Jiayin County]] and [[Heihe City]] *[[Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]] **[[Hulunbuir]]: [[Oroqen Autonomous Banner]]
