A '''Presidential Statement''' is often created when the [[United Nations Security Council]] cannot reach consensus or are prevented from passing a [[United Nations Security Council Resolution|resolution]] by a permanent member's [[United Nations Security Council veto power|veto]], or threat thereof. Such statements are similar in content, format, and tone to resolutions, but are not legally binding.<ref>{{cite book|last=Matam Farrall|first=Jeremy|title=United Nations sanctions and the rule of law|year=2007|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-87802-9|page=21|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4vCVDYufeMsC&pg=PA21#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
The adoption of a Presidential Statement requires consensus, although Security Council members may abstain. The Statement is signed by the sitting [[President of the United Nations Security Council|Security Council President]].
